ce:section.ce:para:
To analyse perfect shape, size and initial structures of synthesized UCQDs and to study their optical and electronic properties, different possible (UCQD)n, (n = 1–16) cluster structures have been computationally analyzed in water environment. For all possible cluster structures both in their ground and excited states were computed to obtain the best optimized structure, total energy, dipole moment, energy band gap by using DFT (Density Functional Theory) [47,65] and TDDFT (Time Dependent Density Functional Theory) The integral equation formalism polarizable continuum model has been used for considering solvation effect [66]. The basic proposed structure of UCQD is a graphene sheet with single layer having a carbon benzene core consisting of C–O–C and C=C basic bonds with the edges ended with nitrogen and oxygen species functional groups such as –NH2, –C=O, –OH, –COOH, -C-O-C- etc. Saturated with hydrogen atoms [67]. We have constructed a series of preferable geometrical layered structures by increasing the number of cores stepwise which represents UCQD behavior at its core surface interface (Fig. 5
                        ). In realistic model, these layers can easily be aggregated to form the bulk phase model [25]. van der Waals forces between graphene layers do not affect the chemical properties of the QD edges, so single layer graphene core systems can be considered as the best possible probe UCQD structures [68]. The dimension of the CQD structure is always proportional to the number of benzene rings present in the proposed structure. For the present case, the proposed (UCQD)n, (n = 1–16) structures were computed for 16 different clusters to find the optimum structure. For each optimized structure different parameters (bond length, bond angle, energy, dipole moment, band gap etc) have been computed and a comparison of few selected parameters are tabulated in Table 2
                        , SD3. For the present case CQDs were synthesized from urea and citric acid. Based on the structural properties of urea and citric acid, typical functional groups like –NH2, –C=O, –COOH, –OH have been considered to passivate UCQDs surface (Table 2). No imaginary frequencies were found during optimization in any of the predicted structures indicating stability of each structure at their minimum energy (SD4). The values of the bond angle and bond length were considered from the inner most carbon ring to explain that each proposed structure has been minimized to its ground state. Usually, electronic, chemical and aromatic properties of graphene core systems are highly dependent on their sizes and edge shapes which determine different aromaticity patterns of the structures created by various functional groups [25,69]. Also the energy band gaps, electronic, chemical and optical properties (absorption, emission spectra) of all CQD structures used to get effected by the presence of different aromatic periodicity in the structure [25].

For the present study, we have computed electronic band gaps, chemical reactivity, absorption, emission and infrared spectra of different proposed (UCQD)n structures and compared them with the experimentally observed spectra to complement the specific chemical structure interpretation. To analyse the effect of functional groups in present UCQDs spectra, the simulated absorption peaks of proposed structures were obtained. All proposed (UCQD)n structures have showed convincing simulated absorption bands in UV–Vis region (Fig. 6
                        ) with peaks associated with π–π* and n–π* transitions (SD5) [70]. Appearance of red shifted weak absorbance has been observed for all suggested (UCQD)n structures for n–π* transition due to the existence of external functional groups at the outer part of graphene core systems whereas blue shifted strong absorbance were appeared due to π–π* from graphene cores [56,71]. For (UCQD)n structures as the number of rings increases in the graphene core, the position of each simulated absorption peaks shifted towards higher wavelength side (Figs. 5 and 6). For all proposed structures, strong absorption appeared within 200–500 nm range as expected from aromatic π graphene cores whereas weak absorption appeared within 500–800 nm from the non-bonded electrons (n) present in functional groups [56]. Absorption peak positions correspond to possible transitions for each proposed optimized structure with their oscillator strength values are tabulated in SD5. The theoretical absorption spectrum of UCQD8 matches closely with the experimental absorption spectrum of synthesized UCQD (Fig. 7
                        ). Due to presence of more UCQDs there is a possibility of some intermolecular interactions between UCQDs which can cause red shift in absorption maxima. For computational optimized single UCQD structure the simulated absorption maxima were observed at 323.21 nm and 407.08 nm whereas for experimental absorption the absorption maxima were obtained at 341 nm and 432 nm. For the further studies UCQD8 structure has been considered as base CQD which constitute the two benzene units as single layered graphene core (Fig. 5).

For better identification of the structural characteristics of core graphene layer and surface functional groups present in synthesized UCQDs, FTIR spectra of simulated and synthesized UCQDs were analyzed and compared within the vibrational region of 500–4000 cm−1 (Fig. 9
                        ). For synthesized UCQD, a broad and wide vibrational band appeared within the range 2800–3800 cm−1 centered at ∼3100 cm−1 due to three stretching vibrations of –OH (νOH) (3200-3700 cm−1) [72], –NH2 (νNH) (3520 and 3400 cm−1) of present functional groups on the surface of UCQDs and also due to the presence of –CH (νCH) (3333-3267 cm−1) modes of graphene core [73]. Broadness of the observed band may be due to the formation of hydrogen bonding between the present functional groups (-NH2, –C=O, –OH) present on the surface of UCQDs with the water environment. Computed FTIR spectrum of UCQD8 structure shows some sharp vibrational stretching modes from νOH at 3757 cm−1, νNH at 3628 cm−1 and νCH at 3175 cm−1 (Table 3
                        ). Presence of νOH and νNH stretching vibrational modes again authorize the presence of –OH and –NH2 functional groups top of the surface of synthesized UCQDs which makes the QDs hydrophilic and in turn enhance their solubility and stability in water [22]. In lower energy region synthesized UCQDs have also shown some major peaks at 1737.45 cm−1, 1581.09 cm−1, 1447.27 cm−1, 1357.09 cm−1, 1221.81 cm−1, 1129.45 cm−1 and 1008.72 cm−1 (Fig. 9, Table 3). Appeared peak at 1737.45 cm−1 is related to stretching mode of the -C-O (νCO) which confirms the presence of carboxyl group (-COOH) in synthesized UCQDs. Peak at 1581.09 cm−1 corresponds to N–H bending (δNH) vibrations. Peak at 1447.27 cm−1 is associated with the C=C stretching (νCC) vibration and symmetric and asymmetric stretching vibrations of C–O–C groups (νCOC). Existence of C=C stretching mode further approves the existence of carboxyl group in present UCQD. Peaks at 1357.09 cm−1 may arise due to bending mode of –OH (δOH) due to the presence of carboxyl group [74,75]. Similarly blue shifted lower energy peaks at 1221.81 cm−1, 1129.45 cm−1 and 1008.72 cm−1 may arise due to stretching (ν), bending (δ), wagging (γ), scissoring (χ) vibrations of sp2 and sp3 hybridized –CH bonds from graphene core of UCQDs. Appearance of stronger vibrational modes of νCO, νNH and νOH justifies stronger presence of carboxylic and amino functional groups on synthesized UCQD surface. The computed FTIR spectrum of CQD8 exhibits similar vibrational peaks for νCO, νNH and νOH modes but blue shifted and sharp in shape compared to experimental FTIR of synthesized UCQDs (Table 3). Therefore, FTIR results further validate the surface passivation of synthesized CQDs by amino and carboxylic groups as surface passivation agents which may significantly improves the luminescence of prepared UCQDs (will be discussed in next section).
